### What problem does this feature solve?
Currently vue compiler generates anonymous function expressions for each event handler with modifiers or handlers which contains expression inside. That is not efficient because resulting `render` function creates new functions each time component is re-rendered. This increases time of garbadge collector work, especially on mobile devices. It becomes even worse when we declare event handler inside `v-for` because `render` function instantiate new functions for each iteration despite the fact that they are the same

**Example** :

```html
<template>
  <div>
     <a href="#" @click.prevent="toggleVisibility">toggle</a>
     <div v-for="todo in todos">
            <input @keydown.enter="saveTodo(todo)" v-model="todo.title">
     </div>
  </div>
</template>
```

The compiled render function looks like this:

```js
        return _c('div', [_c('a', {
            attrs: {
                "href": "#"
            },
            on: {
                "click": function($event) {
                    $event.preventDefault();
                    return toggleVisibility($event)
                }
            }
        })
.....
```

By caching event handlers we could decrease amount of created garbage (i.e., functions) and speed up resulting `render` function

### What does the proposed API look like?
I propose to add a cache object to every `Vue` component instance. That object will hold references to event handlers generated by compiler. And compiler should generate code like this for handlers which compiles to function expression:

```js
"click": _z["click.0"] || function($event) {
   $event.preventDefault();
   return toggleVisibility($event)
}
```

This task can be split into 3 parts:
1. Cache event handlers outside `v-for`. This is quite easy, we just create a cache object per each `Vue` instance and generate a unique id (e.g., integer) for every element which has event handlers
2. Cache event handlers inside `v-for`. I don't see an easy way to do this. However, if we could associate iteration scope with an element then we would be able to cache that handlers as well. So, the resulting handler for `keydown` may look like this:

```js
"keydown": _z["keydown.1"] || function($event) {
    if (!('button' in $event) && _k($event.keyCode, "enter", 13, $event.key, "Enter")) return null;
    return saveTodo($event.currentTarget.__vforScope__.todo)
},
```
3. We will need to update Vue hot loader api to clear handlers cache when template is updated (similar to how static functions cache is cleared)

I can work on both PRs for this feature if you are ok with the proposed changes

